In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims September 2012 as National Childhood Cancer Awareness Month. He acknowledges that childhood cancer remains a leading cause of death for children under the age of 15 and highlights the ongoing efforts to understand, treat, and control the disease. The 5-year survival rate for childhood cancers has increased to 80% due to advancements in research and treatment. The President also emphasizes the support provided to families battling pediatric cancer, including the Affordable Care Act's provisions that prevent insurance companies from denying coverage or placing lifetime dollar limits on treatment. He pays tribute to the individuals and communities involved in fighting pediatric cancer and encourages all Americans to join him in the commitment to combating this disease.